<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-282-185  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 282 185.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Systems Management  Jan 1989 v40 n1 p38(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Utilizing the trend of end user development.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Liu, James P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>End users are more active in systems development.andP;  This is theresult of increased general computer literacy in nontechnicalpersonnel, the information center concept and, most importantly,the acceptance of structured analysis techniques.andP;  Advantages tohaving end users active in systems development include reduceddevelopment time and end products better suited to the users'needs.andP;  A big disadvantage is that inconsistency may be introducedinto the system.andP;  The best way to take advantage of this trend isto coordinate the establishment of guidelines for structuredtechniques and user-analyst training.andP;  Guidelines should be setfor data flow diagrams, data dictionary and processingdescriptions.andP;  User training should be on basic concepts,application modeling and using automated analysis tools.andP;  Systemsanalysts should be trained in the company's business goals and incommunication skills.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     System DevelopmentEnd UsersUser-Written SoftwareTrendsProgramming.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>